column99: Monroe County household hazardous waste garage
column153: At "Waste Management" building, taking refuge under poured concrete column at SW corner. Photographed one small curly-tailed lizard (probably Leiocephalus carinatus?) basking at SW corner of Waste Mgmt building (near Mile Marker 100.1 of US Route 1). Tail was more red than I recall seeing with prior specimens observed on Key Largo. My work vehicle and equipment are stored at this building, so I am here often, yet this was first Leiocephalus I have seen in this area. I've observed others near MM 92 and MM 103.6 and in north Key Largo. The property behind this one accepts vegetative debris from residents and businesses all day, a likely source of dispersal for this species.

column99: Crocodile Lake Wildlife Refuge Administration building
column153: On the 180-degree bend of a wheelchair access ramp, at southwest corner of Crocodile Lake Wildlife Refuge office building (a double-wide trailer elevated approximately two feet above grade). A dense planting of golden beach creeper (Ernodea littoralis) and a deep accumulation of leaf-litter under the ramp and elevated building create ample cover. The property also has poured concrete pad: ADA parking space, and a concrete pad under the air-conditioner unit, providing just the type of solid cover under which Leiocephalus seems to prefer to burrow as well as a constant supply of dripping fresh water (condensate draining onto the concrete pad from the air conditioner). Two northern curly-tailed lizards (Leicephalus carinatus armouri) were observed on August 28; neither as large as they grow, though both looked large enough to reproduce. Refuge Manager Jeremy Dixon got to see the smaller one basking on the ramp's raised decking, just before it hid. Walking behind the building for another view, we found a second slightly larger Leiocephalus running toward the location of the first across the back of the building. I retrieved my camera from the car, but a black racer (charcoal gray Upper Keys color form) showed up and the lizards remained hidden. The place was and (as of Sep 13) is swarming with very small to full-sized Anolis sagrei. Despite efforts by several people, Leiocephalus were not seen at that location again until I got photos of the larger one on September 12, within a meter of where we lost sight of it on August 28. Approximately September 5, Dixon saw what may have been a third Leiocephalus just 35 meters north of the other sightings, midway along the back fence of CLWR's storage yard. He also had another sighting in front (east) of the office, very close to where the first two were seen.

column153: At 5:30PM on June 17, 2013, I noticed one adult Leiocephalus dead on road (DOR) in eastbound lane of divided Barracuda Boulevard. Returned after midnight and collected specimen and voucher photos. I had observed a slightly smaller Lieocephalus approximately three months earlier, basking in same right-of-way in front of 494 Barracuda Boulevard, then a few weeks later in front of 490 Barracuda Boulevard. I returned several times to remove it using manual noose pole, but could not find it again. I suspect this is the same individual, and that it moved two months east. I typically walk a circuit through this subdivision (Anglers Park) once to three times daily and have not seen more than one Leiocephalus at any time in the past two years.

column69: Key Largo, 494 Barracuda Blvd
column99: Seasonal residence of Mario Villoch et al, at 494 Barracuda Blvd., Key Largo
column153: Observed what appeared to be a solitary adult curly-tailed lizard basking on pavers of a home at 494 Barracuda Blvd.) that is used on weekends and holidays by one or more families from Miami-Dade County. The residents often brought with them trailered boats and other vehicles on which a lizard might have been a stow-away. I returned later that day, and regularly for weeks afterwards, but have not seen the lizard since the first sighting. However, I do not have access to most of this lot, and it is a large fenced property, and with a fenced field of 1 or 2 acres adjacent on its east side. I heard later (from neighbor Tilman Wood at 486 Barracuda Blvd.) that a teenager staying at #494 had crossed the vacant property (#490 Barracula Blvd.) between their houses while shooting at iguanas with a pellet gun; leading me to hope at the time that the Leiocephalus had been eliminated (it was not). I was certain at the time that I had the genus correct (99.9%), and somewhat less certain (80%) that I correctly ruled out the other likely Leiocephalus species. Site revisited on 11-Sep-2011. Second , smaller lizard observed and voucher specimen collected.
